    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-12-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-12-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="341"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d341">
                <head>341. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName>) to Secretary of State
                        <persName corresp="#p_MES_1">Muskie</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d341fn1">Source: Department of State, Bureau
                        of Intelligence and Research, Intelligence Liaison Files, TIN 980643000012,
                        Box 6, Afghanistan 1980. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-12-18">December 18, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President has read an intelligence report reflecting Soviet concern over
                    passage of the anti-Soviet Afghan resolution at the <gloss target="#t_UN_1"
                        >UN</gloss>.<note n="2" xml:id="d341fn2">A likely reference to an article in
                        the National Intelligence Daily that summarized a report [<hi rend="italic"
                            >text not declassified</hi>] December 2, which noted that the Soviets
                        sought to “vitiate” the resolution adopted on Afghanistan in the <gloss
                            target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> General Assembly. (Central Intelligence
                        Agency, Office of the Director of Central Intelligence, Job 81B00401R:
                        Subject Files of the Presidential Briefing Coordinator for <gloss
                            target="#t_DCI_1">DCI</gloss> (1977–81), Box 7, Afghanistan
                        Crisis—December 1980, NIDs) For <gloss target="#t_UNGA_1">UNGA</gloss>
                        Resolution 35/37, see <ref target="#d337fn3">footnote 3, Document
                        337</ref>.</note> The Soviets are anxious lest they lose non-aligned support
                    over the Afghan issue. The intelligence community has initiated planning to make
                    Afghanistan a major issue at the February 9–12, 1981, Non-Aligned Nations
                    Foreign Ministers’ Conference in New Delhi and suggests that it is not too early
                    to energize the entire <gloss target="#t_US_1">U.S.</gloss> foreign policy
                    establishment toward the goal of defeating the Soviets in New Delhi. The
                    President noted, “I agree.”<note n="3" xml:id="d341fn3">At the bottom of the
                        memorandum, an unknown hand wrote: “<gloss target="#t_CIA_1"
                            >CIA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_DDO_1">DDO</gloss> wanted to do something
                        through the <gloss target="#t_CA_1">CA</gloss> infrastructure, but <gloss
                            target="#t_NEA_1">NEA</gloss> (<persName corresp="#p_CJ_1"
                            >Coon</persName>) was unenthusiastic, and nothing more was done.” The
                        notation is dated February 9, 1981.</note> (S)</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Zbigniew Brzezinski</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
